curvature(P, diffusion_powers=8, aperture=20, smoothing=1, avg_transition_probabilities=True, precomputed_powered_P=None)

Same as the curvature function, but uses pytorch as backend instead of numpy. Works on both tensors and COO sparse tensors.

Testing with the Karate Club

We'll start with a graph which is simple enough to visualize, so we can see exactly what the diffusion curvature is doing.

print(f'Number of features: {dataset.num_features}')

{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
from torch_geometric.utils import to_networkx
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import networkx as nx
def visualize_graph(G, color):
    plt.figure(figsize=(7,7))
    plt.xticks([])
    plt.yticks([])
    nx.draw_networkx(G, pos=nx.spring_layout(G, seed=42), with_labels=False,
                     node_color=color, cmap="OrRd")
    plt.show()
{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
from torch_geometric.utils import to_networkx
G = to_networkx(data, to_undirected=False)
visualize_graph(G, color=data.y)
{% endraw %}
